<article>
    <h1>BMW 4-se&#xAD;ries Con&#xAD;vert&#xAD;ible gets a boost</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201003/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-03"><time>2020-10-03</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MOTORING</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The new BMW 4-se­ries Con­vert­ible (above) will have a 48-volt “mild hy­brid” pow­er­train. The 440i xDrive Con­vert­ible’s 48-volt starter-gen­er­a­tor and a sec­ond bat­tery al­low far more brak­ing en­ergy to be re­gen­er­ated and stored. This en­ergy is used to sup­ply the elec­tri­cal sys­tem, lighten the com­bus­tion en­gine’s work­load and in­crease its power.</p>
    <p>The starter-gen­er­a­tor pro­duces an elec­tric boost ef­fect that in­stantly de­liv­ers an ad­di­tional 11hp for over­tak­ing or even quicker get­aways off the line.</p>
    <p>There will be other en­gine op­tions, in­clud­ing a to­pline 374hp straight-six driv­ing all four wheels, and two four-cylin­der petrol units gen­er­at­ing 184hp in the 420i sDrive Con­vert­ible and 258hp in the 430i sDrive Con­vert­ible.</p>

